# Popular Networking Tools - Comprehensive Guide

## Network Scanning & Discovery

### Nmap (Network Mapper)
**Description:** Industry-standard tool for network discovery and security auditing.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Basic host scan
nmap 192.168.1.1

# Scan specific ports
nmap -p 22,80,443 192.168.1.1

# Service version detection
nmap -sV 192.168.1.0/24

# OS detection
nmap -O 192.168.1.1

# Aggressive scan
nmap -A 192.168.1.1
```

**Documentation:** https://nmap.org/docs.html  
**Installation:** Available on Linux, Windows, macOS via package managers or official website  
**Use Cases:** Port scanning, service discovery, network inventory, security assessments

---

### Wireshark
**Description:** World's most popular network protocol analyzer for packet capture and analysis.

**Common Usage:**
- Capture live traffic from network interfaces
- Apply display filters: `tcp.port == 80`, `ip.addr == 192.168.1.1`
- Follow TCP streams to reconstruct conversations
- Export packet data for further analysis

**Key Features:**
- Deep inspection of hundreds of protocols
- Live capture and offline analysis
- Rich VoIP analysis
- Cross-platform support

**Documentation:** https://www.wireshark.org/docs/  
**Installation:** Download from wireshark.org for all major platforms  
**Use Cases:** Network troubleshooting, protocol analysis, security analysis, educational purposes

---

### tcpdump
**Description:** Command-line packet analyzer, the CLI alternative to Wireshark.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Capture packets on interface
tcpdump -i eth0

# Capture specific host traffic
tcpdump host 192.168.1.100

# Capture and save to file
tcpdump -w capture.pcap

# Read from saved file
tcpdump -r capture.pcap

# Capture HTTP traffic
tcpdump -i eth0 'tcp port 80'
```

**Documentation:** https://www.tcpdump.org/manpages/tcpdump.1.html  
**Installation:** Pre-installed on most Unix/Linux systems  
**Use Cases:** Quick packet captures, scripting, remote server troubleshooting

---

## Network Diagnostics

### ping
**Description:** Basic network connectivity testing tool using ICMP echo requests.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Basic ping
ping google.com

# Send specific number of packets
ping -c 4 192.168.1.1

# Set packet interval
ping -i 2 192.168.1.1

# Flood ping (requires root)
ping -f 192.168.1.1
```

**Documentation:** Part of iputils package, man pages available  
**Use Cases:** Connectivity testing, latency measurement, network availability checks

---

### traceroute / tracert
**Description:** Displays the route packets take to reach a destination.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Linux/Mac
traceroute google.com

# Windows
tracert google.com

# Use ICMP instead of UDP
traceroute -I google.com

# Set max hops
traceroute -m 20 google.com
```

**Documentation:** Built-in system tool, check man pages  
**Use Cases:** Path discovery, identifying network bottlenecks, routing issues

---

### netstat
**Description:** Network statistics tool showing network connections, routing tables, and interface statistics.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Show all connections
netstat -a

# Show listening ports
netstat -l

# Show with PIDs
netstat -p

# Show routing table
netstat -r

# Continuous monitoring
netstat -c
```

**Documentation:** Part of net-tools package  
**Note:** Being replaced by `ss` command on modern Linux systems  
**Use Cases:** Connection monitoring, port usage, routing table inspection

---

### ss (Socket Statistics)
**Description:** Modern replacement for netstat with better performance.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Show all sockets
ss -a

# Show TCP connections
ss -t

# Show listening sockets
ss -l

# Show process using socket
ss -p

# Show summary statistics
ss -s
```

**Documentation:** https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ss.8.html  
**Use Cases:** Socket inspection, network diagnostics, performance monitoring

---

## Network Configuration

### ifconfig / ip
**Description:** Network interface configuration tools.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Show all interfaces (old)
ifconfig -a

# Modern alternative
ip addr show

# Bring interface up
ip link set eth0 up

# Add IP address
ip addr add 192.168.1.100/24 dev eth0

# Show routing table
ip route show
```

**Documentation:** 
- ifconfig: Legacy, check man pages
- ip: https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ip.8.html

**Use Cases:** Interface configuration, IP assignment, network troubleshooting

---

### netcat (nc)
**Description:** Networking Swiss Army knife for reading/writing network connections.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Listen on port
nc -l 1234

# Connect to host
nc example.com 80

# Port scanning
nc -zv 192.168.1.1 20-100

# File transfer
nc -l 1234 > received.txt
nc 192.168.1.100 1234 < file.txt

# Banner grabbing
echo "" | nc example.com 80
```

**Documentation:** https://nc110.sourceforge.io/  
**Use Cases:** Port testing, file transfers, debugging, backdoor (security testing only)

---

## DNS Tools

### dig (Domain Information Groper)
**Description:** Flexible DNS lookup tool for querying DNS servers.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Basic lookup
dig example.com

# Query specific record type
dig example.com MX
dig example.com AAAA

# Query specific nameserver
dig @8.8.8.8 example.com

# Reverse DNS lookup
dig -x 8.8.8.8

# Trace DNS delegation path
dig +trace example.com
```

**Documentation:** https://linux.die.net/man/1/dig  
**Use Cases:** DNS troubleshooting, zone transfers, nameserver testing

---

### nslookup
**Description:** Simple DNS query tool, available on all platforms.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Basic lookup
nslookup example.com

# Query specific server
nslookup example.com 8.8.8.8

# Interactive mode
nslookup
> set type=MX
> example.com
```

**Documentation:** Built-in tool, check system documentation  
**Use Cases:** Quick DNS queries, reverse lookups, basic troubleshooting

---

### host
**Description:** Simple DNS lookup utility with clean output.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Basic lookup
host example.com

# Reverse lookup
host 93.184.216.34

# All record types
host -a example.com

# Specific nameserver
host example.com 8.8.8.8
```

**Documentation:** https://linux.die.net/man/1/host  
**Use Cases:** Quick DNS queries, scripting, simple lookups

---

## Performance & Monitoring

### iperf / iperf3
**Description:** Network bandwidth measurement tool.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Server mode
iperf3 -s

# Client mode
iperf3 -c server_ip

# UDP test
iperf3 -c server_ip -u

# Reverse mode
iperf3 -c server_ip -R

# Set duration
iperf3 -c server_ip -t 30
```

**Documentation:** https://iperf.fr/iperf-doc.php  
**Installation:** Available via package managers  
**Use Cases:** Bandwidth testing, network performance measurement, troubleshooting

---

### mtr (My TraceRoute)
**Description:** Combines functionality of ping and traceroute with continuous monitoring.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Basic usage
mtr google.com

# Report mode (10 cycles)
mtr --report google.com

# Use TCP instead of ICMP
mtr --tcp google.com

# Set packet count
mtr -c 100 google.com
```

**Documentation:** https://www.bitwizard.nl/mtr/  
**Use Cases:** Network path analysis, latency monitoring, packet loss detection

---

### speedtest-cli
**Description:** Command-line interface for testing internet bandwidth using speedtest.net.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Run test
speedtest-cli

# Show available servers
speedtest-cli --list

# Test with specific server
speedtest-cli --server 12345

# Share results
speedtest-cli --share
```

**Documentation:** https://github.com/sivel/speedtest-cli  
**Installation:** `pip install speedtest-cli`  
**Use Cases:** Internet speed testing, ISP verification, bandwidth monitoring

---

## Security & Analysis

### ngrep (Network grep)
**Description:** Pattern matching for network traffic.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Search for pattern
ngrep -q 'HTTP'

# Specific interface and host
ngrep -d eth0 -q 'password' host 192.168.1.1

# Case-insensitive
ngrep -qi 'user'
```

**Documentation:** https://github.com/jpr5/ngrep  
**Use Cases:** Protocol debugging, security analysis, pattern detection

---

### arp
**Description:** Display and modify ARP cache.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Show ARP table
arp -a

# Add static entry
arp -s 192.168.1.100 00:11:22:33:44:55

# Delete entry
arp -d 192.168.1.100
```

**Use Cases:** ARP troubleshooting, detecting ARP spoofing, MAC address discovery

---

### curl
**Description:** Command-line tool for transferring data with URLs.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# GET request
curl https://api.example.com

# POST with data
curl -X POST -d "param=value" https://api.example.com

# Save to file
curl -o output.html https://example.com

# Include headers
curl -i https://example.com

# Follow redirects
curl -L https://example.com

# Authentication
curl -u user:password https://api.example.com
```

**Documentation:** https://curl.se/docs/  
**Use Cases:** API testing, file downloads, web debugging, automation

---

### wget
**Description:** Non-interactive network downloader.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Download file
wget https://example.com/file.zip

# Resume download
wget -c https://example.com/file.zip

# Download entire website
wget -r https://example.com

# Background download
wget -b https://example.com/largefile.iso

# Limit speed
wget --limit-rate=1m https://example.com/file.zip
```

**Documentation:** https://www.gnu.org/software/wget/manual/  
**Use Cases:** Bulk downloads, mirroring websites, scripted downloads

---

## Modern Tools

### htop / iftop
**Description:** Interactive process viewer (htop) and network bandwidth monitor (iftop).

**htop Usage:**
- Interactive process monitoring
- CPU, memory, swap usage
- Process filtering and sorting

**iftop Usage:**
```bash
# Monitor interface
iftop -i eth0

# Show ports
iftop -P
```

**Documentation:** 
- htop: https://htop.dev/
- iftop: http://www.ex-parrot.com/pdw/iftop/

---

### nload
**Description:** Console-based network traffic monitor.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Monitor default interface
nload

# Monitor specific interface
nload eth0

# Monitor multiple interfaces
nload eth0 eth1
```

**Use Cases:** Real-time bandwidth monitoring, network load visualization

---

## Cloud & Container Tools

### kubectl (Kubernetes)
**Description:** Command-line tool for Kubernetes cluster management.

**Common Usage:**
```bash
# Get cluster info
kubectl cluster-info

# List pods
kubectl get pods

# View logs
kubectl logs pod-name

# Execute command in pod
kubectl exec -it pod-name -- /bin/bash
```

**Documentation:** https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/  
**Use Cases:** Container orchestration, microservices networking, cluster management

---

